<DOC><DOCNO> AP890215-0182 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-15-89 2031EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-15 0648</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0661</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Rains, Flooding Continues In Several States</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rains caused flooding Wednesday in Tennessee, Kentucky,Illinois and Indiana and flood watches were posted in a number ofother states.   Nearly 9 inches of rain has soaked parts of western Kentuckysince Sunday, forcing hundreds of evacuations.   In Frankfort, the Kentucky River had reached 4.6 feet above floodstage by Wednesday afternoon, state officials said. The Barren Riverwas expected to crest about 5 feet over flood stage at BowlingGreen, Ky., on Thursday.   Many small streams in southern Illinois and southern Indianaflooded Wednesday morning. In Ohio, the Scioto River was floodingand a flood warning was posted Wednesday for the West Virginiacounties of Cabell, Wayne and Mason.   Flood watches remained in parts of Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana,Illinois, Tennessee, Missouri, Arkansas, Oklahoma and Texas.   In the southern Atlantic, a tropical disturbance sent heavy rainsand gusty winds toward Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands. Thehurricane season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30, putting the tropicaldisturbance well beyond the normal bounds of tropical weather.   ``Of course, we've had hurricanes in March, but this is not atthat stage yet. It's still just an area of disturbed weatherassociated with a low-pressure system,'' said Bob Sheets, directorof the National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables.   Winter weather advisories were posted in parts of Illinois, NewYork, Idaho, and Vermont. A snow advisory was posted in northeastWashington state.   Snow fell Wednesday in northern New England, northeast New Yorkstate, Michigan, northern Indiana, central Illinois, the Dakotas,eastern Montana, eastern Nebraska, Colorado and northern New Mexico.There was freezing rain in parts of Oklahoma, Missouri, Pennsylvaniaand New York state.   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 2inches at Burlington, Vt., and an inch at Bismarck, N.D., Buffalo,N.Y., Chicago, Grand Rapids, Mich., Peoria, Ill., and Syracuse, N.Y.   Rainfall during the same period included 1} inches at Fort Knox,Ky., and almost an inch at Fort Campbell, Ky.   Several cities in the South broke high temperature records forthe date including Augusta, Ga., 82; Cape Hatteras, N.C., 72;Charleston, S.C., 81; Chattanooga, Tenn., 77; Greer, S.C., 74;Huntsville, Ala., 74; Lynchburg, Va., 76; Mobile, Ala., 80; Norfolk,Va., 79; Pensacola, Fla., 76; Roanoke, Va., 78; Richmond, Va., 82;and Savannah, Ga., 82.   The nation's low Wednesday in the Lower 48 was 29 degrees belowzero at Warroad, Minn.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 13degrees below zero at International Falls, Minn., to 86 degrees atMcAllen, Texas.   Thursday's forecast called for snow showers from north-centralKentucky across central Ohio to west-central Pennsylvania. Snow wasexpected to become rain from southern New England across Marylandand west across the Appalachians, from northern Georgia acrossArkansas, Oklahoma and northern Texas. Showers and occasionalthunderstorms were to reach from southeast Texas across Louisiana,southern Mississippi and central Alabama. Snow was to extend fromthe northern Rockies across the Pacific Northwest and change to rainalong the northern Pacific Coast.   Predicted high temperatures were: single digits from the northernRockies across North Dakota; single digits and teens over northernMaine, Upper Michigan, Wisconsin across the upper MississippiValley, South Dakota, northern Wyoming and western Montana; 20s and30s from the central half of New England across the Ohio Valley, theremainder of the Great Lakes, the middle Mississippi Valley, thecentral Plains, Oklahoma, Texas, the remainder of the Rockies, thePacific Northwest and the northern coast of Washington; 40s and 50sfrom southeast New York state across Delaware and Maryland, much ofVirginia, western Tennessee, Arkansas, northern Texas, southernRockies and the Pacific Coast from central Washington throughcentral California; 80s from southeast Louisiana across Florida.High temperatures will generally be in the 50s and 60s in theremainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>